      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(1)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            The palate, including the hard and soft palate, plays a role in
            modifying the resonance of the vocal tract. It helps shape the oral
            cavity, which, in turn, affects the sound produced during speech.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(2)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            The vocal cords are the primary sound-producing elements in the
            larynx. When air from the lungs passes through the glottis, the
            tension and position of the vocal cords determine the pitch and
            loudness of the sound.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(3)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            The soft palate is involved in sound production by controlling the
            passage of air between the oral and nasal cavities. When the soft
            palate is raised, it closes off the nasal cavity, directing all
            airflow through the mouth for oral sounds.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(4)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            The hard palate's firm structure helps in articulating specific
            speech sounds, particularly those that involve contact between the
            tongue and palate, such as some consonant sounds.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(5)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            The back of the head and the pharynx (throat) aren't directly
            involved in sound production, but play a role when the tongue is
            placed against them.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(6)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            Teeth play a role in articulating speech sounds by helping to shape
            and control the airflow when the tongue or lips interact with them.
            An example is the [Î¸] at the end of the word teeth.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(7)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            The tongue is a crucial articulator for speech sounds. Its
            movements, placement, and contact with other parts of the mouth,
            such as the palate, teeth, and alveolar ridge, contribute to the
            production of a wide range of speech sounds.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(8)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            The face, including the nasal passages, influences the quality of
            sounds by shaping the resonant cavities. Nasal sounds are produced
            by allowing air to escape through the nasal passages during speech.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(9)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            The lips are essential in forming speech sounds, especially bilabial
            sounds (sounds produced with both lips), such as "p," "b," and "m."
            They also contribute to lip-rounding in some vowel sounds.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="popup" style="display: none">
        <div class="popup-content">
          <button class="closeButton" onclick="closePopup(10)">Close</button>
          <p class="additional-text">
            The thyroid cartilage is not directly involved in sound production
            but plays a protective role for the vocal cords, which are
            responsible for sound generation. It helps maintain the stability of
            the larynx and protects the vocal apparatus.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
